SCENE 2: THE RAGGED FLAGON
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
Function: Party gathers intelligence from the Thieves Guild. Orion can learn about Grelod's pipeline. Everyone can learn about the Thalmor presence and buy supplies. This scene costs TIME on the Esbern clock.
Location: A massive underground cistern converted into a tavern. The Ragged Flagon sits beneath the canal, built into the old sewer infrastructure. Water channels run along the edges. The ceiling is vaulted stone. It is warm, lit by dozens of lanterns, and significantly more civilized than the tunnels outside.
THE ROOM (Read Aloud)
"The tunnel opens into a vast underground cistern. Lantern light reflects off black water in channels that ring the chamber. At the center, on a raised stone platform, someone has built a tavern — actual tables, actual chairs, a bar made from a repurposed merchant's counter, and shelves of bottles behind it. A fire burns in a stone pit, and the smoke curls up through a vent in the ceiling.
A dozen people occupy the space. Most are drinking. Some are playing cards. A Dunmer woman behind the bar is pouring mead with the practiced efficiency of someone who has been doing this for twenty years. Near the fire, a broad-shouldered Nord with red hair sits in a high-backed chair like it's a throne, listening to a younger man report something in a low voice.
The conversation doesn't stop when you enter, but it quiets. Eyes track you. Hands move to belt-lines. After a long five seconds of assessment, the room collectively decides you're not guards and returns to its business."
Then improvise from: The warmth after the cold tunnels. The smell of actual food — bread, stew, something roasting. The sound of water flowing in the channels. Playing cards snapping on wood.
WHAT'S IN THIS ROOM
The red-haired Nord by the fire (Brynjolf): What they see: A broad-shouldered man sitting like a king in a sewer. If they investigate: Brynjolf runs the Thieves Guild's Riften operation. He is Maven's primary criminal lieutenant. He knows about Grelod's pipeline. Why planted here: He's the social boss of this scene. Information comes through him.
The Dunmer bartender (Vekel the Man): What they see: A professional bartender. If they investigate: Vekel sells drinks, potions, and rumor. He's the easiest NPC to talk to. Why planted here: Low-stakes social entry point. Information about the Warrens and the Vaults.
The younger man reporting to Brynjolf: What they see: Someone delivering information. If they investigate: This is Delvin Mallory. If Orion was directed here by Dirge, Delvin is his contact. Why planted here: Connects to Orion's Guild intelligence thread.
THE PEOPLE
BRYNJOLF (Guild Master) Voice: Warm, expansive, friendly in the way a shark is friendly. Scottish-coded accent. Calls everyone "lad" or "lass." Body language: Relaxed, open posture. Never stands unless he wants to intimidate. Drink always in hand. Attitude: Amused. The Obsidian Lanterns are famous. Their name is on the wall upstairs. Cooperates for: Mutual benefit, entertainment, anything that inconveniences Maven's enemies. Pisses him off: Moralizing about theft. Threatening his people. Mentioning the Guild's name out loud.
Opening line: "Well, well. The Obsidian Lanterns, in the flesh. Or... most of them." He counts heads. Notices Kyboh's absence but doesn't press. "What brings Riften's heroes to its least reputable establishment? And don't say 'the ambiance.'"
If asked about:
Topic
Response
The Thalmor / the elves
"Aye, they came through. Four of them. Paid well, said nothing, went down. They're after the old scholar in the Vaults. Been expecting this for years, honestly. Poor bastard."
Esbern
"Esbern. Quiet old man. Pays his rent in gold coins that are decades old. Never causes trouble. Buys food from my people and retreats to his hole. Whatever he did to make the Thalmor want him dead, he did it a long time ago."
Grelod the Kind
His expression doesn't change, but his eyes do. "Grelod is a pillar of this community. Beloved by all. A living saint." The words are perfect. The delivery is rehearsed. He's reciting a press release.
Grelod (pressed harder, Guile TN 16)
He leans forward. "Grelod is an investment. Her orphanage produces... talent. Talent that we train, employ, and compensate fairly. If someone is asking about disrupting that arrangement, I'd want to know who's asking and why."
The Warrens
"The Warrens are where Riften puts the people it doesn't want to look at. Argonians, addicts, the sick, the mad. We don't bother them. They don't bother us. If you're going down there, bring coin — not for spending. For giving. It buys good will, and good will is the only currency that works below the Flagon."
Helping with the Thalmor
"I'm not sending my people against Justiciar kill squads, lass. That's not theft — that's war. But I'll tell you this for free: the elves went through the Warrens to reach the Vaults. They left a mess. You'll see it."

DELVIN MALLORY (Guild Fence / Intel Broker) Voice: Cockney-coded, gravelly, conspiratorial. Talks out of the side of his mouth. Body language: Fidgets. Picks at his nails. Never makes eye contact for more than a second. Attitude: Professional. If Orion has the token, Delvin treats him as a colleague. Cooperates for: Brotherhood credentials, gold, interesting information. Pisses him off: Being patronized. Being lied to (he can tell — Guile 16).
Opening line (if Orion presents the token): Delvin looks at the nightshade. Looks at Orion. Nods once, very small. "Alright. What does the family need?"
If asked about:
Topic
Response
Grelod's operation
"Grelod runs a training program. Kids come in orphans, they come out with skills. Best pickpockets in the Rift start at Honorhall. Brynjolf handles placement. Maven handles protection. It's clean. Efficient."
Constance Michel
"The assistant? Quiet girl. Does the actual caring-for-children bit while Grelod does the... other bit. Scared of her own shadow. Scared of Grelod more. We told her years ago — keep your mouth shut, keep your job, keep breathing. She keeps her mouth shut."
The orphanage layout
"Two floors. Main hall downstairs — that's the public face. Kitchen, dining room, dormitory for the little ones. Upstairs is Grelod's quarters, the training room, and storage. One entrance, front door. Back window in the kitchen opens onto the canal. Grelod locks the training room at night with a Master-level lock."
Honorhall's guard schedule
"No guards. Grelod doesn't need them. She IS the security. The kids are too afraid to run and too trained to disobey. The Guild checks in once a week — that's Thursdays. Don't hit it on a Thursday."

