SCENE 5: ESBERN'S BUNKER
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
Function: Esbern delivers the Dragonstone quest, provides Dragon Cult expertise (including Forelhost context Alfonso needs), and plants the Sky Haven Temple seed. This is the reward scene — information, not combat.
Location: A cramped, reinforced chamber at the bottom of the Ratway Vaults. One room. No exits except the door the party just came through.
THE ROOM (Read Aloud)
"The key turns. Three locks disengage. The door swings inward on oiled hinges — the only well-maintained thing in the entire Ratway.
Inside is a room no larger than a prison cell, and it has been one for thirty years. Every surface is covered. Maps pinned to the walls with iron nails — Skyrim, Cyrodiil, Akavir, places you don't recognize. Charcoal diagrams of dragon skeletons annotated in a cramped, obsessive hand. Stacks of books rising from the floor like stalagmites, some open, some marked with strips of cloth. A cot. A chamber pot. A small desk buried under papers. A cold plate of bread and cheese that hasn't been touched.
An old man stands in the center of this paper fortress. He is perhaps seventy. His beard is long and grey and wild. His eyes are red-rimmed and enormous behind the lenses of a pair of cracked reading spectacles. He holds a dagger in one shaking hand and a lit torch in the other — ready to burn everything rather than let it be taken.
He stares at you. He is trying to decide if you are here to kill him or save him. The dagger shakes. The torch does not."
Then improvise from: The smell of old paper and candle wax. The absolute silence — deepest point of the Ratway, no sound reaches here. The organized chaos of a brilliant mind in a very small space.
WHAT'S IN THIS ROOM
The maps on the walls: What they see: Maps of Skyrim with dozens of locations marked. If they investigate: Dragon burial mounds. Esbern has been mapping them for thirty years using historical records, folklore, and reports from agents. But the map is incomplete — he needs the Dragonstone to finish it. Why planted here: Visual setup for the Dragonstone quest.
The charcoal dragon diagrams: What they see: Anatomical drawings of dragon skeletons with annotations. If they investigate: Esbern has been studying dragon physiology through bones and historical texts. His notes reference "tonal vulnerabilities" — frequencies that could disrupt a dragon's connection to Akatosh. This is theoretical. He needs Alduin's Wall to confirm. Why planted here: Establishes Esbern's expertise. He's not just a scared old man — he's the foremost living expert on dragons.
The stack of books marked with cloth strips: What they see: Flagged reference texts. If they investigate (Magic or Guile TN 12): Historical accounts of Dragon Priest tombs, including entries on Forelhost. Esbern has annotated the margins. If Alfonso asks about Forelhost specifically, Esbern lights up — see Moves below. Why planted here: The bridge between Alfonso's Meadery lead and Esbern's expertise.
The cold bread and cheese: What they see: An untouched meal. If they investigate: He's been too scared to eat since his agent (Caius) failed to arrive. He knows something went wrong. Why planted here: Human detail. This man has been terrified and alone.
THE PEOPLE
ESBERN (Last of the Blades) Voice: Educated, precise, rapid when excited, halting when afraid. He speaks like a lecturer who forgot he has an audience — then suddenly remembers and gets self-conscious. Germanic cadence. Body language: Nervous hands. Adjusts his spectacles constantly. When he talks about dragons, the fear vanishes and academic passion takes over — he stands straighter, gestures broadly, his eyes focus. Attitude: Terrified → Grateful → Urgently passionate (in that order, over the course of the conversation). Cooperates for: Anyone willing to fight dragons. Anyone who brings news of Caius. Pisses him off: Dismissing the dragon threat. Suggesting surrender. Being told to calm down.
Opening line (once he realizes they're not Thalmor): The dagger lowers. The torch stays up. "You... you're the Lanterns. The ones from Kynesgrove. From the Pale." His voice cracks. "Is Caius with you? My agent — he was supposed to be here two days ago. Imperial man, courier's leathers, carried a—" He sees their faces. He reads the answer before they speak. The torch lowers. He sits on the cot. "Ah."
If they give him Caius's letter: "[He reads it in silence. His hands stop shaking. When he looks up, his eyes are wet but his voice is steady.]" "He found it. He found Alduin's Wall. And they killed him for it." A long breath. "Then we must go ourselves. Before the Thalmor reach it first."
If asked about:
Topic
Response
The Blades
"We were the Dragonguard. Akaviri warriors sworn to hunt dragons and serve the Dragonborn. After the Great War, the Thalmor hunted us to extinction. I am the last. Thirty years in this hole, waiting for the world to need me again. It does now."
Why the Thalmor want him dead
"Because I know things they don't want anyone to know. I know about the Towers. I know about their protocol to unmake the world. And I know about Alduin's Wall — a prophecy carved in stone by the Akaviri that tells how to defeat Alduin without a Dragonborn."
The Dragonstone
"A map. A complete map of every dragon burial mound in Skyrim, carved into a stone tablet by the ancient Nords. It's in Bleak Falls Barrow, overlooking Riverwood. With it, we stop reacting and start hunting. We find the mounds BEFORE the dragons rise."
Alduin's Wall / Sky Haven Temple
"Sky Haven Temple is the last Blades sanctuary. Hidden in the Karthspire, in the Reach. Alduin's Wall is inside — a massive stone carving that depicts the defeat of Alduin in the Merethic Era. It describes a Shout called Dragonrend, which forces a dragon out of the sky and into mortality. It is the key to everything."
The Tower Protocol (if they show him the documents)
His face goes grey. He reads them twice. "I knew they wanted to unbind the Towers. I didn't know they'd formalized it as military doctrine." He taps Document 2. "This is a genocide order. Not of a people — of a plane of existence. They want to dissolve reality itself." He looks at the party. "Do you understand? The dragons want to enslave the world. The Dagon cult wants to burn it. The Thalmor want to erase it. Of the three, the Thalmor are the ones with a plan that could actually work."
Forelhost
[His eyes sharpen. Academic hunger takes over.] "Forelhost. The Last Redoubt. You want to know about Forelhost?" He pulls a book from a stack without looking. "During the Dragon War, when the ancient Nords overthrew their Dragon Priest masters, most priests surrendered or fled. Not Rahgot. Rahgot retreated to Forelhost with his entire congregation — thousands of people. When the Nord army besieged the fortress, Rahgot ordered mass suicide. Every man, woman, and child drank poison rather than submit to a world without dragons. Rahgot sealed himself in the inner sanctum and entered a death-sleep." He pauses. "The Nords never breached the inner sanctum. They simply sealed the fortress and left. The dead are still inside. All of them."
Antoine / the plague maker
"A living Dragon Cult alchemist operating out of Forelhost? That is... deeply concerning. If he has access to Rahgot's sanctum, he has access to the biological resources of a mass grave — thousands of preserved corpses, alchemical reagents cultivated in a sealed environment for thousands of years. It would be the perfect laboratory."

THE MOVES
ALFONSO → FORELHOST INTELLIGENCE
What he wants: Context for the plague architect he's hunting. What's required: Asking Esbern about Forelhost.
Ask Esbern about Forelhost └─→ Esbern provides the historical context (mass suicide, Rahgot's death-sleep, sealed inner sanctum). └─→ If Alfonso describes the pathogen: Esbern nods slowly. "An artificial plague cultivated in a sealed, sterile environment rich in preserved organic material and ancient alchemical reagents. Forelhost is not just a tomb. It is a laboratory that has been incubating for four thousand years."
